         <head>
            <title>Witness Statement Provided by Mrs. Charlotte Shelby</title>
            <date>April 9, 1926</date>
            <orgName>Police</orgName>
         </head>
         <div>
            <byline>Eleanor Luciani</byline>

            <sp select="question">
               <speaker>POLICE:</speaker>
               <ab>During the time in <placeName>the east</placeName> there, when he <persName
                     ref="#taylor_william">(Taylor)</persName> was directing her
                     <persName ref="#minter_mary">(Mary)</persName>, did you observe any awakening of a friendship or
                  love between the two of them?</ab>
            </sp>

            <sp select="answer">
               <speaker>MRS. SHELBY:</speaker>
               <ab> No.</ab>
            </sp>

            <sp select="question">
               <speaker>POLICE:</speaker>
               <ab>When did you first see that, or did you at all?</ab>
            </sp>

            <sp select="answer">
               <speaker>MRS. SHELBY:</speaker>
               <ab>I never did know it, Mr. Keyes, until <persName ref="#mott_john"> Mr.
                     Mott</persName> told me of the <objectName type="communication"
                     >letters</objectName> that had been found in <persName ref="#taylor_william">Taylor's</persName>
                  <objectName type="furniture"> drawer</objectName> that absolutely is convincing that there had been
                  something there.</ab>
            </sp>

            <sp select="question">
               <speaker>POLICE:</speaker>
               <ab>You mean after he was killed?</ab>
            </sp>

            <sp select="answer">
               <speaker>MRS. SHELBY:</speaker>
               <ab>Yes, and <persName ref="#eyton_charles">Mr Eyton</persName> told me also after <persName ref="#taylor_william">Mr.
                     Taylor</persName> was killed that he knew that, that he knew for a long time
                  that <persName ref="#minter_mary">Mary</persName> and <persName ref="#taylor_william">Mr. Taylor</persName> had been
                  intimate, and I said then <quote>"<persName ref="#eyton_charles">Mr. Eyton</persName> you should have
                     told me"</quote></ab>
            </sp>

            <sp select="question">
               <speaker>POLICE:</speaker>
               <ab>During that time, <persName ref="#shelby_charlotte">Mrs. Shelby</persName> (referring to latter part of
                     <date>1919</date> and early part of <date>1920</date>), was
                  <persName ref="#minter_mary">Mary</persName> going around with <persName ref="#taylor_william">Taylor</persName> to your
                  knowledge at all?</ab>
            </sp>

            <sp select="answer">
               <speaker>MRS. SHELBY:</speaker>
               <ab>Why no, and <persName ref="#taylor_william">Mr. Taylor</persName> was the most perfectly poised man,
                  such a proper man. He would take <persName ref="#minter_mary">Mary</persName> out to dinner and he
                  would invariably invite me and my mother to go to dinner with them.</ab>
            </sp>

            <sp select="question">
               <speaker>POLICE:</speaker>
               <ab>Did you make any objections?</ab>
            </sp>

            <sp select="answer">
               <speaker>MRS. SHELBY:</speaker>
               <ab> Not the least in the world.</ab>
            </sp>

            <sp select="question">
               <speaker>POLICE:</speaker>
               <ab>Were you friendly with him?</ab>
            </sp>

            <sp select="answer">
               <speaker>MRS. SHELBY:</speaker>
               <ab>Oh, yes. **</ab>
            </sp>

            <sp select="question">
               <speaker>POLICE:</speaker>
               <ab>Do you remember anyone in particular with whom she was associating at that
                  time?</ab>
            </sp>

            <sp select="answer">
               <speaker>MRS. SHELBY:</speaker>
               <ab>It wasn't men. Men hadn't begun to give me any trouble at that time. It was
                  women.</ab>
            </sp>

            <sp select="question">
               <speaker>POLICE:</speaker>
               <ab>Who was that?</ab>
            </sp>

            <sp select="answer">
               <speaker>MRS. SHELBY:</speaker>
               <ab><persName>Jeannie McPherson.</persName></ab>
            </sp>

            <sp select="question">
               <speaker>POLICE:</speaker>
               <ab><persName ref="#taylor_william">Taylor's</persName> name never entered into the discussion then?</ab>
            </sp>

            <sp select="answer">
               <speaker>MRS. SHELBY:</speaker>
               <ab>No. I always felt that, when <persName ref="#minter_mary">Mary</persName> was out with <persName ref="#taylor_william">Mr.
                     Taylor</persName> she was under a good influence. **</ab>
            </sp>

            <sp select="question">
               <speaker>POLICE:</speaker>
               <ab>Did you ever have any words with <persName ref="#taylor_william">Mr. Taylor</persName> over
                     <persName ref="#minter_mary">Mary</persName>?</ab>
            </sp>

            <sp select="answer">
               <speaker>MRS. SHELBY:</speaker>
               <ab>Never a word, never the slightest word. (Speaking of the time <persName ref="#shelby_charlotte">Mrs.
                  Shelby</persName> went to <persName ref="#taylor_william">Taylor's</persName>
                  <placeName>home</placeName> at <time>2 a.m.</time> looking for
                     <persName ref="#minter_mary">Mary</persName>) </ab>
            </sp>

            <sp select="question">
               <speaker>POLICE:</speaker>
               <ab>Did this secretary of yours, <persName>Miss Whitney</persName>, go in the
                     <placeName>house</placeName> with you?</ab>
            </sp>

            <sp select="answer">
               <speaker>MRS. SHELBY:</speaker>
               <ab>No, I know she didn't because there was nobody in the <placeName>room</placeName>
                  but <persName ref="#taylor_william">Mr. Taylor</persName> and me. She stayed in the
                     <objectName type="vehicle">car</objectName>.</ab>
            </sp>

            <sp select="question">
               <speaker>POLICE:</speaker>
               <ab>Did you have any <objectName type="weapon">weapon</objectName> with you at that time?</ab>
            </sp>

            <sp select="answer">
               <speaker>MRS. SHELBY:</speaker>
               <ab>Good lord, no.</ab>
            </sp>

            <sp select="question">
               <speaker>POLICE:</speaker>
               <ab>You are sure you didn't have a <objectName type="weapon">revolver</objectName> with you?</ab>
            </sp>

            <sp select="answer">
               <speaker>MRS. SHELBY:</speaker>
               <ab>No, <persName>Mr. Keyes.</persName></ab>
            </sp>

            <sp select="question">
               <speaker>POLICE:</speaker>
               <ab>Well, you owned a <objectName type="weapon">revolver</objectName> at that time?</ab>
            </sp>

            <sp select="answer">
               <speaker>MRS. SHELBY:</speaker>
               <ab> No. If I owned a <objectName type="weapon">revolver</objectName> at that time, I don't know
                  where it was. It was thrown away.</ab>
            </sp>

            <sp select="question">
               <speaker>POLICE:</speaker>
               <ab>What date was it when you were at <persName ref="#taylor_william">Mr. Taylor's</persName> home that you
                  were telling about?</ab>
            </sp>

            <sp select="answer">
               <speaker>MRS. SHELBY:</speaker>
               <ab>I think I could almost fix that date, <persName>Mr. Keyes</persName>, referring
                  to a certain little <objectName type="miscellaneous">book</objectName>, you know. Because I was reading
                     <persName ref="#minter_mary"> Mary's</persName>
                  <objectName type="miscellaneous">diary</objectName> and she goes on to say in this
                     <objectName type="miscellaneous">diary</objectName> that she and I had some little words that
                     <time>evening</time>, you see, and she has written it very cleverly, about the
                  small girl going out in a huff, etc., and she adds that mother was right. ** And I
                  think the date of that happening is right in her
                  <objectName type="miscellaneous">diary</objectName>.</ab>
            </sp>

            <sp select="question">
               <speaker>POLICE:</speaker>
               <ab>Did you ever make a threat to kill <persName ref="#taylor_william">Mr. Taylor?</persName></ab>
            </sp>

            <sp select="answer">
               <speaker>MRS. SHELBY:</speaker>
               <ab>No, <persName>Mr. Keyes.</persName> I never had any reason or desire to kill
                  <persName ref="#taylor_william">Mr. Taylor.</persName></ab>
            </sp>

            <sp select="question">
               <speaker>POLICE:</speaker>
               <ab>And you are positive, are you,<persName ref="#shelby_charlotte"> Mrs. Shelby</persName>, that you never
                  at any time threatened <persName ref="#taylor_william">Mr. Taylor?</persName></ab>
            </sp>

            <sp select="answer">
               <speaker>MRS. SHELBY:</speaker>
               <ab>Certainly not, I had no reason. I never threatened to shoot <persName ref="#taylor_william">Mr.
                     Taylor</persName>. I don't think I ever threatened to shoot any man.</ab>
            </sp>

            <sp select="answer">
               <speaker>MRS. SHELBY:</speaker>
               <ab>To shoot him? No, because I had no reason. I had no provocation. I never had a
                  quarrel with <persName ref="#taylor_william">Mr. Taylor</persName> in my life.</ab>
            </sp>

            <sp select="question">
               <speaker>POLICE:</speaker>
               <ab>You spoke of having thrown a <objectName type="weapon">gun</objectName> away?</ab>
            </sp>

            <sp select="answer">
               <speaker>MRS. SHELBY:</speaker>
               <ab>No, my mother did that.</ab>
            </sp>

            <sp select="question">
               <speaker>POLICE:</speaker>
               <ab>That was your <objectName type="weapon">gun</objectName>?</ab>
            </sp>

            <sp select="answer">
               <speaker>MRS. SHELBY:</speaker>
               <ab>The <objectName type="weapon">gun</objectName> was given to me in <placeName>Santa
                     Barbara</placeName> by <persName>Harry Eaves</persName>, who has a
                     <placeName>jewelry shop</placeName> up there - a very short little
                     <objectName type="weapon">pistol</objectName> - a little <objectName type="weapon">automatic</objectName> -
                  ** and he said to me, <quote>"I have got two and you ought to have
                  one."</quote></ab>
            </sp>

            <sp select="question">
               <speaker>POLICE:</speaker>
               <ab>Where did you say you shot it once?</ab>
            </sp>

            <sp select="answer">
               <speaker>MRS. SHELBY:</speaker>
               <ab>I got a friend of mine to take me out in <placeName>Santa Barbara</placeName>,
                  just off the <objectName type="miscellaneous">road</objectName>, and we shot it into a
                     <placeName>bank</placeName> and I shot it once.</ab>
            </sp>

         </div>

